<br>
Just be sort of &quot;chivalrous but not stupid,&quot; taking careful note of guilds that abuse your hospitality.  You get mutual treatment and the whole game is less stupid and boring.  HOW TERRIBLE.  <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/bsullonzektavern.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=minidas>Minidas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tavern Regular</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/4/01 5:51:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3914.topic&index=152>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: IE Defeats DB &amp; TDC, Ruin monk comments on PvP and D</span><hr size=1> Think of it as practicality if it pleases you.  As you pointed it out, there is no clearly defined &quot;goal&quot; in EQ, so it's up to you to define that goal as &quot;being as cruel and unpleasant as possible to anyone I am able to attack.&quot;  The rules of VZ said nothing about crossteaming; you arbitrarily, and correctly, enforced the rule that pure-teaming was more fun.  It was WEAKER though, wasn't it?  Shocking.  You didn't use the tool at your disposal, a immo healing human cleric.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   I don't think there's any such thing as honor in gaming. Honor goes against the point of gaming.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What a stupid sentiment.  What possible dry, shriveled twitch could it give you to win, AT A GAME, dishonorably?  People that feel this way should go find a bloody Nietzsche discussion group and leave normal well adjusted people to play computer games while they slowly implode.<br>
<br>
Analogies to chess or poker are retarded.  How do you act cheap in a game of chess?  You can't suddenly play a game of chess with someone while he's already got 10 other games of chess agroed on him.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
I basically think that the justification for actions like this, (that were called &quot;griefing&quot; when they were illegal, if you no longer prefer the term) are specious.  They're based on laughably false analogies and philosophical tracts that are either Nietzschean or fascisty, depending on your level of distaste.  War to the utmost, etc etc.  It's all false logic.  Behavior is constrained by social norms in most cases, not by the absolute limits of the rules.  If you don't believe me, ask yourself, if you saw a random enemy, would you delevel him 59-54?  Do you bindcamp?  Do you kill people you meet randomly on CRs?  Most people find this stuff fucking petty.  <br>
<br>
You don't have to be Don Quixote not to be a prick. You just have to play the game like a person and not like some angst-ridden adolescent who just read about the Will to Power.  <br>
<br>
What kind of fuckup plays football caring ONLY about the rules and not sportsmanship?  Anyone who really, honestly only cares about winning, period, in the games they play is tragic.  People say that because it sounds cool, but if you care about winning more than fun... eh.... what the fuck are you?<br>
<br>
<br>
On a different note, for those of you who insist on behaving as if this is some grand darwinian struggle, why don't you take the example of WWII fighter pilots, who didn't strafe parachutists jumping out of aircraft in most cases?  <br>
<br>
Why didn't they?  Partly because it's a fucking low thing to kill someone helpless in cold blood.  Partly because pretty soon everybody would do it if someone started.  Sound like anything we know?  An analogy is never a proof, but this one is actually fairly close.  An important distinction is the stakes involved, but as you seem intent to behave as if the game should be played to the bitterest extremity...<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/bsullonzektavern.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=minidas>Minidas</A> at: 10/4/01 6:09:51 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/uagrul.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Agrul</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Message Board Warrior</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/4/01 6:24:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub73.ezboard.com/fsullonzektavernfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3914.topic&index=153>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: IE Defeats DB &amp; TDC, Ruin monk comments on PvP and D</span><hr size=1> &quot;If you are supposed to be maximally hostile by every means neccesary, shouldn't you be using 3rd party software that can't be detected and fabricating complaints to GMs to try to get the other guilds disbanded? It's war after all.&quot;<br>
<br>
Could I?  Yes.  Should I?  Maybe.  Do I?  No.  I set my own personal guidelines, not those of other players - it isn't going to kill me if Jakka wants to use ShowEQ to make the game that much easier, so why should I try to tell him he can't?<br>
<br>
&quot;If not, then you've chosen an arbitrary line of &quot;shitiness&quot; that you won't cross. And since that line is arbitrary, why not set it at a less irritating place?&quot;<br>
<br>
Yup, I've set my own *personal* guidelines, with no attempt to hinder the choices others may make.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, I enjoy the place it's at now.  I don't find it irritating in the least.<br>
<br>
&quot;There's no sense in defending something that you personally would not do. Would you do this?&quot;<br>
<br>
I defend freedom of action within virtual environments, regardless of whether or not I agree or disagree with a person's actions.  There's plenty of reason to defend something you wouldn't do.<br>
<br>
&quot;Bind camping an AFK is NOT PvP&quot;<br>
<br>
I agree.  That doesn't make it an unfair, unethical, and immoral practice though, /shrug.<br>
<br>
